---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const repo = 'jaredcat/plushonscreen';
---

<Base
  title="About PlushOnScreen"
  description="PlushOnScreen is a fan-run database of IKEA plush toys spotted in movies, TV, and music videos. Learn how to submit a sighting."
>
  <h1 style="font-size:clamp(2rem,6vw,3.5rem);margin-top:2rem">About</h1>

  <div class="prose" style="max-width:60ch;margin-top:1rem">
    <p>
      <strong>PlushOnScreen</strong>
      is a community-curated database tracking the appearances of IKEA plush
      toys in movies, TV, music videos, and more. It started with one absurdly
      photogenic green snake — the <a href="/plushes">Djungelorm</a> — and grew
      from there.
    </p>
    <p>
      It's a fan project. Not affiliated with IKEA in any way. Just people who
      keep noticing the same plushie show up in the background of things and
      can't let it go.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 class="section-label">Spotted one? Submit it</h2>
  <div class="prose" style="max-width:60ch">
    <p>
      There are two ways to add a sighting, depending on how comfortable you are
      with GitHub:
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>1. The easy way — fill out a form.</strong>
      No coding needed. Just answer a few questions and we'll handle the rest.
    </p>
    <p style="margin:1.25rem 0">
      <a
        class="btn"
        href={`https://github.com/${repo}/issues/new?template=sighting.yml`}
      >
        Submit a sighting →
      </a>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>2. The direct way — open a pull request.</strong>
      If you know your way around git, add a markdown file under
      <code>src/content/sightings/&lt;plush-id&gt;/</code>
      with the screenshot in that folder's <code>images/</code> directory, and
      open a PR. The schema in
      <code>src/content.config.ts</code>
      shows every field. This gets your sighting live the fastest.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 class="section-label">What makes a good entry</h2>
  <div class="prose" style="max-width:60ch">
    <p>
      A <em>screenshot</em> is the single most important thing — this is a
      visual catalogue, so a clear still of the plush on screen is gold. Beyond
      that: the title and year, roughly where in the runtime it shows up (a
      timestamp), and a sentence describing the scene. A clip link is a bonus.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
